text:
I am Christian and Pro Family. I believe that the family is instituted by God so that our society can flourish. And nothing should separate a man and a woman bound in marriage.

However, I am also anti violence and anti abuse. If a marriage results into hurting one or both parties (and even the children) physically and emotionally, then why do they need to stay together? Divorce can be a tool to help end an abusive marriage. 

People do make mistakes in choosing a partner that results to an abusive marriage. Why do they need to suffer the rest of their lives because of their mistakes?

But divorce isn't a reason we shouldn't use wisdom when choosing a partner. It's not a get-away-free-card to marry anyone you want without thinking about it twice.

text:
Senators running in the 2025 elections shouldn't be intimidated by the so-called "Catholic vote"—it's a political myth. They should also not be scared to support progressive measures like divorce.

It's truly discomforting to see clerics on television spouting political rhetoric as if they hold the exclusive rights to righteousness, patriotism, and love for the country. It makes my toes curl. Recall how the Catholic Church vehemently campaigned against senators who supported the RH bill, only for the 2013 elections to reveal that most Filipinos are in favor of reproductive health. Similarly, when the Catholic Church attacked Sen. Juan Flavier for distributing condoms as health secretary, he still emerged victorious in the elections.

In 1998, the Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines (CBCP) actively opposed the candidacy of Joseph "Erap" Estrada, issuing pastoral letters and warnings to voters. Despite these efforts, Erap won the presidency with an overwhelming majority.

And in 2016, despite the CBCP issuing guidelines aimed at thwarting the Duterte phenomenon, Duterte won by a landslide. These examples demonstrate that the so-called "Catholic vote" does not dictate electoral outcomes. Senators should feel empowered to support necessary reforms like divorce, which reflect the evolving values and needs of the Filipino people.

Do not dwell on the premise of a battered wife or of the unfaithful husband/wife. Reconsider the feelings of the children affected. Imagine seeing their mother/father remarrying, it does not only break their heart but also their soul. A vow is a vow. You do not marry for yourself but for family. 

Mas sakit tanawon namong mga anak nga kaslon sa nagkalain-lain nga pares amoang ginikanan.

#NoToDivorceBill

Quoted from Lilian Cocjin - Aspra...

Living in a country for many years where divorce is legal, I have seen how devastating it was for the family particularly for the children. Instead of the couple working out their problems and finding solution to preserve their family, they would rather choose the easy way out which is divorce. This results in brokenness not only of the marriage but of every member of the family especially the children. I see children from this broken home confused, lacking in self esteem, problematic in school with anger issues, drug addiction, promiscuosity,etc and eventually they themselves became divorced in their own marriages and the cycle continues. Since family is the fundamental unit of the society, a family weakened by divorce results in a weakened society.
